Min Cost Climbing Stairs problem is defined here: https://leetcode.com/problems/min-cost-climbing-stairs/

I have 2 solutions for this - 1 that takes 1ms to run on the leetcode submission and is faster than 89.65% of Java submissions and the 2nd that takes 2ms and is faster than only 39.33% of the Java submissions on Leetcode. 
I need help figuring out how are the solutions so drastically different in terms of time complexity when they look similar to each other. There must be some nuance I am missing which I want to better understand.


I am sharing the 2 solutions below:

1. Executes in 1ms and is faster than 89.65% of Java submissions:
```
    public int minCostClimbingStairs(int[] cost) {
        // The array&#39;s length should be 1 longer than the length of cost
        // This is because we can treat the &quot;top floor&quot; as a step to reach
        int minimumCost[] = new int[cost.length + 1];
        
        // Start iteration from step 2, since the minimum cost of reaching
        // step 0 and step 1 is 0
        for (int i = 2; i &lt; minimumCost.length; i++) {
            int takeOneStep = minimumCost[i - 1] + cost[i - 1];
            int takeTwoSteps = minimumCost[i - 2] + cost[i - 2];
            minimumCost[i] = Math.min(takeOneStep, takeTwoSteps);
        }
        
        // The final element in minimumCost refers to the top floor
        return minimumCost[minimumCost.length - 1];
    }
```

2. Executes in 2ms and is faster than 39.33% of Java submissions:
```
    public int minCostClimbingStairs(int[] cost) {
        //cost: 0 -&gt;n-1
		//dp: 1-&gt;n
		int[] dp = new int[cost.length+1];
		dp[0]=0;
		dp[1]=0;
		//k=2
		for(int i=1;i&lt;cost.length;i++) {
			dp[i+1] = cost[i] + Math.min(dp[i], dp[i-1]);
		}
		
		return Math.min(dp[cost.length], dp[cost.length-1]);
		
    }
```

